x4freetext: Cross sections for the Ti(n,xn) and Ti(n,x-gamma)
reactions between 1 and 20-MeV
Oak Ridge Electron Linear Accelerator
Annular ring of TI, 1556 gms, 25 cm outer diameter,
15 cm inner diameter, with thickness of 1.05 cm.
Purity of TI better than 99%.
Time of flight used to determine neutron flux.
Flux measurements made with sample and shadow bar
removed. Scattering sample placed 47.8 meters from
source, with shadow bar protecting detector from
direct neutron beam. Time between the linac pulse and
the detection of radiation used to determine incident
neutron energy. Pulse discrimination used to seperate
neutron and gamma events in detector. Background
determined with sample removed.
Pulse height spectra were integrated over intervals
of neutron time of flight data to form new pulse
height spectra of specific incident neutron energy
ranges. Computer code FERD used to unfold new spectra,
which were then normalized to cross sections using the
measured neutron flux, average sample to detector
distance, and sample thickness.
NE-213 on axis at a scattering angle of 130
degrees. Small plastic scintillator placed at edge of
beam, 30 meters from source, to normalize flux to
cross section measurement.
Corrections made for average transmission of incident
neutron flux, average transmission of secondary gammas
or neutrons out of sample, and multiple interactions.
Absolute uncertainty of about 10% in neutron flux
determination (largest source of systematic error).
Transmission correction uncertainties <3%, multiple
interaction correction assigned an error of 10%.
Approved by G.L.Morgan, 1981/5/19.
Reactions corrected. Updated to new date
formats, lower case.
Statistical error is given. Normalization
error of 10% not included.
Backgrounds were from 10% (lowest pulse heights) to 50%
(highest pulse heights).
Corrected REACTION.
